        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "1. Piacere: freely or no tempo. Just play the chords as you want, without tempo."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "2. Andante Moderato: slowly, but not too slowly. Seriously, this is a somber tune."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "Playing it anything faster makes it sound like a happy song about hard times, which is"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "somewhat contradictory to the tone, don?t-cha-know?"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "3. A tempo: return to previous tempo, which, as listed, is piacere."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "4. This is one of those cross-style songs. What I mean by that phrase is that this can"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "be flat picked or finger picked. Strumming all the way through this song makes it seem"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "kind of boring, so add some dynamic arpeggiations just to spice things up."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "5. The history behind this song is rooted deeply in Appalachia; a culture of music and"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "dance that originates from a mountain ranges on the east coast appropriately named the"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "Appalachian Mountains. The history of this song in particular is more or less a"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "popularization of the Appalachian style. Written by Stephen Foster, the song shares a strong"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "cultural bond with Appalachia, as well as its sister songs ?Oh, Susanna? and ?Camptown"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "Races?, which were also written by Foster. Most of this music appeared in what?s known as"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "the ?minstrel show?, which was more or less a vaudeville style performance during the"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "late 1700 and 1800s. You could find all sorts of fun things at the minstrel show: dancers, actors,"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "jugglers, contortionists, etc?But what you really went there for was the music. There"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "weren?t public venues or theaters back then; the minstrel show was literally a variety"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "show on wheels. This format, more or less, is how the cultural music of Appalachia was"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "spread throughout the country. That being said, Appalachia draws its heritage from none other"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "than the green island of ï¿½ire, which is why I decided to chord out this song."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "6. Well, that, and I?m a huge fan of the Chieftains. Paddy Moloney, the player of the"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "uilleann pipes for the Chieftains, actually shares the same clan as my family. (The clan Moloney)"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "7. As such, since this arrangement is by and Irish band, the song is in D. Go figure"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "that an Irish song would be in D."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "8. As always, if you have requests for acoustic music, please send them my way."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "chunks": [
            {
              "chord": null,
              "lyrics": "9. Adh mor! (Good luck)"
            }
